<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-610-887  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 610 887.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Nov 19 1990 n1557* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Where architecture-neutral distribution formats were demonstrated.andO;(at Open Software Foundation's members meeting in Boston, MA)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Open Software Foundation (Conferences and meetings).andO;Topic:     New ProductConferences and MeetingsConsortiaSoftware ArchitectureTechnology.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>WHERE ARCHITECTURE-NEUTRAL DISTRIBUTION FORMATSandM;WERE DEMONSTRATEDandM;The Foundation members meeting provided the first opportunity for members tosee Architecture Neutral Distribution Format submissions actually running.andO;Participants were required to run the software on the machine of their choiceand on one other, to demonstrate portability.andP;  The four submissions includedthe UK's Royal Signals andamp; Radar Establishment running its submission on a DECVAX and an 80386 machine, Hewlett-Packard Co and the University of Virginiaon HP Precision Architecture and 80386, Siemens/Nixdorf on a 80386 machineand a DECstation 3100, and Peritus Inc on Sparc and MIPS machines.andP;  Thedecision whether or not to go ahead, according to the Foundation's Directorof Business Management Marie Burch, lies not so much with the technology -which works, according to the Foundation - but on commercial viability.andP;  Willthe Software Foundation break even or make a profit on it? How will it belicensed? And will it be able effectively to take advantage of futurearchitectures as they emerge? If the architecture-neutral project does getthe nod, we should see the first snapshots very soon, with finished productby the end of next year.andO;</TEXT></DOC>